The Prague Stock Exchange falls into a negative position against closing of business.
After the steep fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions in ČEZ’s shares reached almost half of normal day-to-day business.
The Prague Stock Exchange began trading on Tuesday as a result of the Monday slump when it fell by another six percentage points.
This time the reason for the break-in was Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the reaction of the market to the outcome of the vote by the US House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Case of shares in Asia
On Tuesday, the stock exchanges in Asia experienced a dramatic fall, although the indices were able to offset some of the losses over the course of the day.
The index of the Hang Seng Stock Exchange in Hong Kong lost almost four percentage points during the business day, but was later able to make up for some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which observes the movement of Chinese shares on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while the markets in Shanghai were closed.
The shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but then reduced the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to the index, the stock exchange in Taiwan declined by 3.6 percent.
"The timing of the rescue operation in the US is uncertain and will affect the financial markets worldwide," said Hong Kong's chief monetary authority, Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, even though it is part of China, determines its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese Central Bank.
Hong Kong's interest rates are at the same level as those in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American legislators should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible and adopt the draft financial system support.
Otherwise, other countries would also be affected by the collapse.
A Bloodbath of American Stocks
On Monday, the American House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, for which up to $700 billion (nearly Kč 12 trillion) should be spent.
The legislators thus ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
In Bush's view, the plan would regulate the fundamental causes of the financial crisis and thus help to stabilise the entire economy.
On Monday, the American stocks suffered a bloodbath, and the main stock indices recorded the biggest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones Index fell by almost seven percent, with a similar decline last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there was hardly any evidence that the draft would not get through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concessions: US government is allowed to pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the American Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the American financial system.
The vote will take place at the beginning of next week.
American legislators made a breakthrough in discussions about the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of financial assistance to the American financial system amounting to $700 billion (about $12 trillion).
However, this does not mean victory.
Congressmen still have to negotiate some details of the agreement before they can publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the US Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services, Barney Frank, told Reuters.
In the Senate, according to various sources, the plan could probably not be voted on at the earliest on Wednesday.
According to economists, a communication on the adoption of the plan should be the first major psychological factor for revitalising financial markets.
After that, however, there was a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms that could help the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our different views on what a package to stabilise the market should look like," said the Democrat Nancy Pelosi to the agency Bloomberg.
According to them, a final vote could be held on Sunday.
Legislators met with U.S. Secretary of State Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for the purchase of unsaleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which plunge the financial firms into severe losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must be effective on the market.
You have to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we're at the finish line," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian businesses
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the legislators were trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
The aim is to reassure investors against dealings on Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a congressional decision could affect business on Monday.
So far, however, it is not quite clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, nor is there any clarity as to whether the last minute negotiations could still fail due to a problem.
The legislators hope that it will be adopted in the next few days.
The law, however, will undergo some changes.
The total amount of aid to the system is to be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be made available as soon as possible, as President George Bush demanded.
Congress can, however, block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfil its function, with another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush Appreciates Progress in Negotiations Positively
Although the President has a veto right in this decision, Congress can overrule its veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has remained, which was based on obtaining finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Bush was satisfied with Saturday's progress and "estimated the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
The chairman of the banking committee of the Senate, Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, stated that the legislators had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the conclusion of benefits and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the programme and sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
This is supposed to be headed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this and achieved great progress towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," says Paulson.
The plan also expects help for homeowners who have problems with the repayment of their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new mortgage rates that it buys, with the aim of reducing the monthly costs for debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance's chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but implementation will be very difficult.
"That is because one does not know what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
This will be crucial for how the financial sector and the government share the losses among themselves," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
According to Marek, whether the plan will be adopted now or at the beginning of next week is not decisive.
"It is much more important for Congressmen to agree to support the plan and to adopt it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement that there is a passing is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Duel on Messer's edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can call yet.
So, of course, it looks like it's better to just buy a phone.
Despite all this, there are enough reasons why you should gain an independent player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
I'm sure it's hard to buy a great expensive record player at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
Once such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if you have LPs with kind of rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably dream of at least one.
So it is also with music on travel, i.e. with compressed music, expressed in a simplified way - music in MP3 format.
Here, too, there are price and quality categories.
For one, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand kroner on a player, but a pink-floyd fan will hardly be able to handle headphones for twenty kroner from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
The lifetime of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what mobile phones can do they don't even make sense.
No modern device can be used as universally as the phone.
In addition to primary functions, phone calls and sims, it can play music and videos, record both, it sometimes has a better camera, sometimes a worse one, and may also navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can photograph.
But the universality of mobile phones also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Only a few mobile phones can play music for more than ten-twelve hours, usually much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest) are much more powerful.
Therefore, on cheap phones, you should expect that they can play no more than a few hours of music.
If you then from time to time still call, you prefer to buy yourself a charger for the office for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players you will not have this problem, even the less good keep at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation with one time charging out.
Another problem is when you want to transfer the music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices has a USB termination, and not every phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can transfer the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can handle the tiny memory cards used in mobile phones without any reduction.
For players you do not need any special software except for exceptions (iPod).
You only need to feed the device via USB port with music from your PC.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, sorted by the name of the performer, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the user's rating.
Some devices only represent the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (Iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, intelligent phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When selecting a specific device, you should inquire about the battery life, the storage capacity, the quality and type of sound and of course also the ease of use.
If music is mainly a backdrop for you and if you listen to it every day only briefly in the tram, for example, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which almost every cell phone can do.
You also don't have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can process.
MP3 will create everyone, and most of the music you get will be in this format right now.
The format is one of the most widely used, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better mobile phones also allow you to buy music online.
You only need to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet, and you can purchase a song or album.
This service can in itself be a powerful argument for why you should buy a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is poor and is mostly limited to fast radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of sale of music (whether via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry the phone with them.
If you feel like listening to something, grab the phone in the jacket pocket while the player is at home forgotten.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can rely on the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of the music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand kroner.
You'll get a decent Walkman for three and four thousand kroner.
The biggest handicap will be for most that there are no normal headphones.
The best and most technically sophisticated phones with a 3.5 mm opening for normal headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players in turn lies in the easy operation.
The simplest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - players can really be operated by everyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the previously normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable is obvious.
There is no danger of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequent horrendous invoice for data transmission.
Which device should you grab now
Also the cheapest mobile phones (e.g.Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable storage media (type M2, microSD etc.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are usually supported.
Only the most expensive ones can read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then grab Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
Be among the more demanding listeners, rather take specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have standalone control buttons for MP3, and the ease of use is thus close to that of a single MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman mobile phones have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players, is the furthest.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum up to 35 hours) provide you with MP3 players from the above manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer practically all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic at lower prices.
Maybe he won't be waiting much longer.
We have often reported on Mobil.cz that Czech mobile operators are working at the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by the ČTÚ telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price of a text message is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
Following the European Commission's final steps in the area of roaming charges, there is likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile phone providers SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, because in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and penetration of far more than 100 %.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to scold that there is an extremely high level of competition on the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák often agrees, who in the past had often said that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has much chance (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is still one option - a virtual provider.
The entry of virtual providers into the mobile phone market in particular brought with it a significant price reduction, to which then also the classic mobile phone providers had to react.
Before the entry of companies like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market in Great Britain, there were voices similar to those in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for long examples.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider has managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the country's five largest provider.
Behind Mobilking stands the financial group Penta, which owns among others U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that they can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need far fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers usually emerge as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and text messages, but this is often accompanied by a less comprehensive range of services.
For example, in the UK, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good move to rely on a non-cliche target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose mobileking - the provider they like and who they can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also establish itself in the Czech Republic.
The press spokesman of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of services."
In the Czech Republic, mobile phone providers mean no chance
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile carrier conquers the Czech Republic, it will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very hopeful.
Mobilking will be more likely to enter the market in other countries in our region," says Jana Studničková, Spokesperson of the Penta Financial Group, in a telephone conversation with Mobil.cz.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
For some time now, the GTS Novela group has shown its interest in launching a virtual mobile provider, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the corporate customer sector.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line, but also mobile communications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated this option with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already achieved progress in negotiations with some of them," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times are coming.
Non-official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area", says in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile's spokesperson Martina Kemrová adds, in rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
And she adds: "There will hardly be a virtual provider in the network of T-Mobile by the end of the year.
At this moment, we should already have a concrete offer in order to be able to think in the short term."
Vodafone focuses its attention more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the best from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - hand in hand with the providers
The approach of mobile operators is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, this would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure towards ČTÚ was at the moment when U:fon came onto the market, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also demonstrated by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is a good argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has also recently been strengthened by the entry of a fourth mobile phone provider.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, on its services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
It is not only the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately, unlike the United Kingdom and other highly developed countries, does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, related to this whole problem its very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider by renting the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classical suppliers", said Kristián Chalupa, of the External Relations Department of the ÚOHS, in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not surprise suppliers’ representatives.
This is more than worrying from an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In foreign countries, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction for mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not part of the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking about this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether this is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same gasoline price at the petrol stations is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not detected any signs of anti-competitive action in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way in the matter.
None of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market to virtual providers are likely to be missing from the telecoms regulator," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different perspective - for the market entry of a virtual provider the approval of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile phone provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if this argument is not taken into account, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are doing a strikingly similar thing.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the company GTS Novera mentioned above) show that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The transfer of responsibility to ČTÚ is then quite a common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, in the recent amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of ČTÚ's competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications has not been achieved, although a number of experts have promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS need to know that all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's all right when nobody's looking
The functioning of some pseudo-virtual providers, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains ignored.
They are companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Normally, they are companies that operate in the field of multi-level marketing.
Own mobile telephone services offer for example Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be a violation of the contractual conditions that we will then deal with, which can lead to an end of the cooperation with the corresponding company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question on this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not be heard by the mobile service providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, there may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
In fact, the activities of these companies do not give them negligible profits, but at the same time, unlike the actual virtual providers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out possible problems: "The law allows for such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot have it in its full capacity, as the normal customers of mobile phone providers."
This alone, however, should at least seem strange to the ČTÚ.
There is also another question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes to such a procedure, why are they blocking themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration by the providers that they do not know about it and their terms and conditions would prohibit it.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the entry of virtual providers has led to a significant price decrease in the various services.
In virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged, the classic providers have tried to prevent their emergence practically more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened at these very moments, which did not try to protect the interests of mobile operators, but rather those of their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators throw themselves at the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguities in competences are more than favourable in these cases.
But let us not throw the shotgun into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider appears soon, the Czech mobile phone market may soon start moving again.
If a provider allows the emergence of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally not make more expensive calls than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four versions of the new Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Czech State Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek presented in a ceremony the new recordings of the National Anthem Where is my home country.
The anthem was re-recorded by the orchestra of the National Theatre under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
There are four versions available - with male or female solo vocals, in choral version and in an instrumental version.
The vocals were taken over by Kateřina Kn.nková and Adam Plachetka.
The editors of the hymn versions are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the server iHNed.cz you can listen to all four versions.
For Bělohlávek, the Czech national song is one of the most beautiful hymns.
He had previously told the Czech Radio that he had chosen singers with young, representative voices for the solo versions, which are striking and popular.
"From the beginning, I tried to keep a clear diction on both and then on with the choir, so that the text could be understood well, so that there would be harmony," the conductor said.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song "Kde domov můj" was first performed in 1834 on the stage of the stage theatre in the originally Czech play Fidlovačka by Josef Kajetán Tyl, the music was by František Škroup.
It became popular, and people spontaneously accepted it.
The first verse of the song became an organic part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
It remained one of the seven state symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
