Prague transport companies will also be transporting on a chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008, will go down in the history of Prague's transport companies as a date when the first passengers who carry an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket will enter a metro, tram or bus.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and play it on their chip card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádra
Since yesterday, coupons are also available via the Internet on the websites of the transport companies www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use Internet sales can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have had to wait regularly in long queues for their paper tickets.
They buy the coupon via the Internet, which is played on the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, travellers are also provided with a desk with trained staff, which advises those interested in buying the Internet and also places the coupon on the card," said the spokesperson of the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, electronic coupons can also be played on the opencard on self-service machines, which are installed in some underground vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket devaluers, passengers may have noticed them already in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are currently five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there will be eighty," adds Opatrný.
The coupon is controlled by an automatic machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
All you have to do is insert the chip card, and the coupon you bought before is self-explanatory.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
Thus in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which especially the inhabitants from municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia reach the capital.
"In the trains that are part of Prague's integrated transport system, train attendants have readers to check the validity of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid. This organisation compiles the timetables for Prague's transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the driver's desk.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be shown to the driver, but the open card must be placed in a marked position at the side of the cash register.
The driver thus checks the validity of the coupons played.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons, nothing is easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not use suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon ends can again go to the self-service machines where the coupons are played on the card.
Here the information about the validity of its documents is displayed on the display of the device.
