With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the US president in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian scientific library.
In the letter the Germans of Krumau ask the American President not to allow the return of the "Sudetungus" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and we really want to be sure of the words that the American units do not enter German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says a letter signed with the words "people to whom the fate of the Sudeten lies at the heart".
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia leads the Sudeten Germans - knowing the Czech national character - to suspect that they would expect brutality, ruthlessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you are acknowledging this territory to a state that is foreign to us, which oppresses and tries to eliminate minorities and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the U.S. president had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he initiated a referendum in the Bohemian Forestgau on whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the U.S. or live under the protection of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naive in today's knowledge of post-war history, according to some contemporary witnesses, it paints a good picture of the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans at least had to suspect that they would negotiate their deportation from the Republic, only a few of them admitted such a possibility at all.
Some waited for the United States and Great Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Others believed that they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who comes from Budweis.
He was employed in the Baltic Sea Navy as a Budweiser German during the war.
When he was taken into British captivity at the end of the war and was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens of other Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them," said Chalupa.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war expected that they would be expelled from the Republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
