This amazing success has been achieved by other methods than those preferred by Obama.
The school Sixth Street places its emphasis on testing and practice, on constant control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach of training in an English-speaking environment, which is exactly what Obama is supposed to consider, according to headmaster Linda Mikels.
This approach attaches importance to the almost exclusive use of the English language in technical instruction.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me that the school had a remarkable success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico. 12 months later, they would enter the classroom and no longer recognize him.
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The performance of the school would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational positions within his own party (the national image associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While agreeing with the point that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the subject by remarking that people should stop worrying about legislation aimed at "only English".
Instead, he said, "You should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama really wants to close the gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work instead of scorning and trivializing them.
