The pride and the hardships in the life of the black population, in a city of a very special kind
Hidden between the exuberances of the amusement parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, noisy and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture come to light.
Eatonville, the first completely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquets, 300 brown skins, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
Today it is a pilgrimage site.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have come to the annual Zora! Festival in Eatonville to commemorate the most famous author of the Harlem Renaissance.
And yet the city she describes – and which made her a tourist destination by taking her to the Florida guidebook produced by the Federal Writer's Project at the time of the Depression – is in many respects a very special place.
Eatonville is as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black communities in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with the white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't know what he's missing."
Even today, in a year when a black presidential candidacy, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open conversation on racial relations, many here are still tired of being watched by outsiders.
"We are very concerned about how our story is told," says Hortense Jones, 59, a resident of the city from birth and a member of the congregation of the city's oldest church.
It must be true."
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It is both a historical example of the black movement and a community of almost 2,400 inhabitants in which the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is on the one hand a stronghold of literature and on the other hand an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural South, which has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And the concerns about Eatonville's image really started with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that leads through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the locations of black history and human drama.
Naughty as Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Beyond the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown-white painted modern school, with its well-kept gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, although he can hardly read and write."
She also mentioned the new husband of widow Dash and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever suits hour rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, second marriage, and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by all.
"Zora described things as they were," said 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about their beauty, full of sexual allusions.
She added, "Some people didn't like this."
Hurtson is still remembered here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came to the city, she usually did so without warning, in a noisy Chevrolet, smoking and wearing trousers, in a city that even today imagines something of her venerable dress style.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, while many despised them.
"People were always happy to see Zora," said Mr Franklin.
But "she never stayed too long," he added while rocking in his chair, on a back-facing terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of print.
Together with most of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten it.
Although she was once a famous writer, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
In Eatonville there was no big memorial, no public readings on a large scale.
"I don't think they understood their contribution to the world or their heritage at all," says Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
The turn came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's slow two-lane main street.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult phase in his history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred into the community.
"During this time, a bunch of white boys often came and threw oranges and stuff at the people sitting away," said Mr. Franklin.
"There was even once a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request to force integration by calling its decision in the Brown case against the school council "infringing rather than respecting my race."
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being hugged - I remember - hugging his teacher in the morning and hugging his teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and managing director of the non-profit group to protect the Eatonville community.
This could be maintained for so long, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"They didn't hug his white teacher, because he was a white teacher - I mean there is a cultural divide," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped to create space for further Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who overturned prejudices, as they did, with positive self-confidence and statements such as: "How can anyone deny the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker set out for Hurston's nameless tomb and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much acclaimed Hurston biography of Robert E. Hemenway was found on the bookshelves, and again made it part of the American literary canon.
The highway project came exactly at a time when Eatonville’s most famous daughter was once again in the public light.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, speeded it up at top speed, and aroused real civil pride," said Ms. Nathiri.
Mrs Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the highway project has contributed to a change in the city's self-image.
More and more people arrived, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to re-evaluate the past.
Eatonville was included in the national historical register in 1998.
A new one-storey library (of course named after Hurston) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today Eatonville is still a special feature in Florida: only 6 miles from Orlando city centre can it sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It's 90% black these days.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its meaning are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, permission is required in advance and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church, painted by a white man and depicting black men in the field work - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Mrs. Jones, a courageous, self-confident teacher with a penchant for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston Festival grew, an elevated degree of home pride was born.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her whole race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and diligent, silly and mixed up as any other race and ethnic group in America.
It is the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city administration or the police, who according to him could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just pass through here will think, "Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others," said Alondra Kenon the other day on a Sunday after the church.
"But if you actually stop and look at your story for a moment, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York people speak fluently financial Latin.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the newsstands and the huge TV screens in Times Square, they would not realize that they were in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, daily have the worst horror day since the 1929 stock market collapse.
The suppliers are still pushing the metal tea machines along sidewalks with loud rattles and carrying trays loaded with muffins for breakfast sessions.
Latinos are still slurping between apartments, like human pack animals loaded with around 50 ironed T-shirts hanging on a yoke-like rod on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting on the sidewalks for dinner on their breakfast bagels and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4 pm and 7 pm.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, due to all the doomsday talk, I decided to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to put my duty on the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase branch, about 20 people were already standing in line.
Not at the cash counters to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists for directions to Macy's department store, and where new customers open accounts.
Most of the people in front of me, so I later learned from Starr, my "personal bank clerk with a license," were standing in line for the same reason as I was.
Unlike me, however, they had already removed their savings from smaller banks, in places from where they commuted, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called Thrifts (a little like a building savings bank), cooperative banks and those local savings banks that only have branches in one state, saying that they treat their customers as a family.
Last year, 15 of these banks went quietly bankrupt.
In the last few days, Washington Mutual, a $327 billion bank, went into bankruptcy management, and when New Yorkers last Friday drove home for the weekend, Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion in savings, was looking for a rescuing buyer.
In the fear of another collapse, the office and shop staff standing in front of me brought their cash to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank that is responsible for most rescue purchases on Wall Street.
In recent weeks, ordinary New Yorkers have acquired a fluid financial Latin.
A woman who was on the phone in my Chinese parent super market was so familiar with Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank and its emaciated-looking CEO Dick Fuld, as if she were blaspheming at a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my block of flats has dropped from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my food delivery.
