Her dancing was sensual and I was told that my dancing is also in this aesthetic area,' she claims.
The production anticipates two extraordinary collaborations: Miguel Poveda, who will sing again for Isabel at one of her performances, as he did in 'La puerto abierta'; and Flamenco master Matilde Coral, who wanted to work with one of her ex-students.
Matilde plays Tórtola, a very mature personality.
I am happy because she agreed to participate in my work, and I am very honored.'
The production also includes musical composition and the guitarists Jesús Torres and Paco Arriaga, the vocals of Miguel Ortega, el Pulga and Moi de Morón; the percussion of El Pájaro, as well as the viola of Rafa el Viola and the collaboration with actor Juanfra Júarez, he 'takes over the role of companion of the artists who were divas, to whom he falls in love again and again.'
This work also tells in a certain way about the life of this woman, who became known in places as far away as India, the United States or Russia, and also throughout Europe, although she normally lived in London.
