According to statistics, between 30-75% of drivers who have been reported more than once for driving under the influence of alcohol have returned to driving.
The `alcolock' would prevent this because it is a system connected to the car, it measures the alcohol content in the exhaled air and prevents auto-start if the driver has done alcohol test; or if an alcohol concentration higher than allowed is determined.
It costs more than EUR 1 000 and the costs are borne by the person who imposes the penalty.
In this context, a study carried out in the US in 2007 showed that cars equipped with these devices prevent up to 65% of standard violations in the first year after its introduction.
In Spain, 115 lives are expected to be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to tackle this behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate their implementation, a legislative reform can be implemented by ordinary means, and yet a reform of the Basic Law is required, which is necessary for the prosecution process.
The device is not yet available in any business in the Spanish markets, although it has already been installed in some commercial vehicles and public transport vehicles.
