Sarkozy meets angry fishermen
Before he flies to the United States, Nicolas Sarkozy will make a detour to Brittany.
In view of the determined attitude of the fishermen who blocked access to several Breton and Norman ports on Monday, the French President decided to come to the port of Guilvinec in the Finistère on Tuesday morning to meet with their representatives.
The latter promised to receive him 'with a constructive spirit' and hope that he will come with 'concrete proposals'.
The President's visit takes place at the same time as a General Assembly of the Crisis Committee, which was founded by the Breton fishermen to enforce measures in view of the extreme increase in the price of diesel, which has reached a record value of over 1.14 euros per litre on average.
According to the spokesman of the Elyséepalast David Martinon, "the President will discuss with them possible solutions to help their companies to become competitive again, and to ensure the working conditions and the payment of seafarers".
Sarkozy is expected with determination by the fishermen.
Tuesday morning, they led protest marches in Morbihan and Calvado, causing congestion of nearly ten kilometers in length.
The sailing port of Quiberon was also blocked, but the connections to Belle-île did not break off.
The Quiberon Peninsula was demarcated by a barrier.
Already on Monday, the sailors expressed their determination by burning tires and pallets from early morning in front of the fuel depots of the ports of Brest and Lorient, while demonstrations were held in Concarneau or Saint-Brieuc.
The movement extended to other ports of the Atlantic coast and the English Channel, such as Sables d`Olonnes, in Vendée, where the fishing boats did not go out, or Le Havre, where about twenty boats blocked the maneuvers of the merchant ships.
The fishermen of Turballe and Croisic in Loire-Atlantique dissolved the blockade of the major total refinery in Donges in the evening.
The Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait for the meeting to take place at the Ministry on Wednesday before deciding on possible measures.
Indeed, the crisis committee in Guilvinec has to decide on the reactions to the movement and its participation in the discussion planned at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
But some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by those responsible for the national fisheries committee who did not support their movement.
'The strike will continue', because 'the fishermen will not give in at all' and 'do not want to go to Paris', announced Liliane Cariou, president of the Lorient Fisheries Committee.
The professional fishermen who do not pay taxes on diesel currently cost about 50 cents of the litre, but they think that the profitability limit of a boat can only be reached with diesel for less than 30 cents per litre.
