Conversation - From the blood that became safe again
Yesterday Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its President, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to be happy, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, it has regained public confidence, which was severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As we know, the national blood reserves administered by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HIV virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, in February 1994, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to draw up guidelines to prevent a new catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitant to submit his report, several provinces set up a committee to develop a new system for managing canned blood in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood canning system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood cans and through the work in this field during the following years, we have regained public confidence', she says, before she proudly emphasizes that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of the population of Quebec now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that 'trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its foundation on 28 September 1998, Hema-Quebec has been acting on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the emergence of numerous cases of the human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, this woman, who has been in charge since its inception in 1998.
"And we had no idea at all whether this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we referred to one of the main guidelines of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which exclusion measures are applied if one does not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was accepted from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt, it was proved that this disease was transmitted through the blood.
So this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has a purpose.
In 1999, a much more accurate technology for the detection of HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which enable the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the donor's blood, and not that of the antibodies to the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to less than one week.
Thus, the risk of certain donors being infected without knowing it, and not being able to recognise it, has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are in danger of receiving HIV - infected blood.
In other words, it means distributing 12 million cans of blood before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 cans of blood every year, it would take more than 24 years before a case of HIV being transmitted via a can of blood occurs.
I believe that you can feel comfortable these days when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore your health,' says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know which pathogen can get into the system.
Only last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted through the blood by insects.
We have to monitor continuously', Dr. Décary continues, before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must provide sufficient supply in addition to a secure supply.
'The need increases because the population ages.
Since cancer treatment is more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which on average includes only 3% of the population of Quebec eligible for blood donation.'
Any healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who make their blood available are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have travelled to a country where malaria is common are excluded from blood donation for a year.
`With these 3% we manage to get an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of supplies is very rare.
But it is necessary to renew the members of this donor network when they get older and can no longer donate blood.
It is hard to convince people to donate blood, but above all to keep it and make it become regular donors.
Life is so hectic these days that you rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood," regrets Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec not only supplies blood, but also human tissues, including bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is used almost exclusively for severe fire injuries.
These tissues are examined, processed and frozen before being temporarily stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
In the umbilical cord, formerly considered a biomedical waste, there is blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat severe diseases such as leukemia.
A few weeks ago we celebrated the storage of our thousandth umbilical cord blood sample, and we plan to lose more than a thousand annually.
"We should probably start making it available for transplants early next year," explains Dr. Décary, who describes this program of umbilical cord blood loss as very popular.
'Many mothers are convinced that they do not have access to it', because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all hospitals in Quebec.
