We are not yet aware of this, but we are currently experiencing a insidious circumcision of our rights, our freedom and our 'democracy', this word that Harper constantly carries before him like a flag, and that sounds so meaningless from his mouth.
So the time has come when there is no more morality: one can arbitrarily abuse, torture and imprison a Canadian citizen, at the discretion of a head of government, who is still only supported by the minority (may he be a minority after 14 October...).
Many voters believe that they can find their salvation in a party that preaches virtue, law and order, but they do not see that this government has renounced what constituted the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr Toews, is in this lotion, and nowhere else.
Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Vice-Director-General of the Canadian Barrick Gold Gold Mine.
This confirms, and in doing so follows an Orwellian logic that the world's largest gold mining company sought a six million libel lawsuit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening a 'public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of libel claims, but rather the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
For Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and editors of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid from the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics of these unequal struggles, moreover, are often to ruin the defenders in order to impose a consensual settlement that silences the other side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her point of view to public opinion.
In contrast to what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates are usually held in Canada through the exchange of ideas and not by clubs.
So it would have been enough if the gold mine had disclosed its books and files and opened up a real debate through which newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams could have shed light on this issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to have no confidence in public opinion and wipes away the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand move.
Could Mr Garver perhaps explain how he could at the same time ask for a 'public' debate and yet disregard the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, in the Vice-President's world, this word only includes the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a rather cramped view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public, who supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does this mainly because it rejects the brutal attitude of the gold mine.
This public is willing to listen to and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, and not within a framework that many perceive as a gag complaint (in the course of the 'public debate', Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada, in which they demand that they no longer use this term...).
Apart from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's complaint is a direct attack on freedom of academic research and truth-finding, which are fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to quote credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and discuss issues that the rich companies of the world do not like, who else can do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could lead it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to deal with debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate complaint clearly shows that, contrary to what she claims, she does not want a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate, and it is time for governments to take measures to limit this type of unjustified complaint.
Rescue for Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans get along
The Bush administration and senior congressmen, Republicans and Democrats alike, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the most comprehensive economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan, which is supposed to stop the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months, still needs to be adopted by the two congressional chambers.
The main elements are: better control by MEPs over the practical application of the plan, new mechanisms to ensure the repayment of public funds used, new arrangements to limit the number of houses pledged for arrears, and the right to monitor the salaries paid to the executives of the supported companies.
The American Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, President of the Chamber of Deputies Nancy Pelosi, and Senator Judd Gregg, the Republican representative present at the negotiations, announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes after midnight, after a two-day marathon.
'We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be marketable,' said the Bush administration representative, Henry Paulson.
'Everything was done to protect the real economy and the American people from the Wall Street price crisis,' the Democrat declared.
'This is the basic point: if we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and unrest in American daily life will be enormous,' explained Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had accelerated during the last two hours, for fear of the effect that a renewed failure would have had on the mood of investors.
The deadline that had been agreed was the market opening this morning.
The two American presidential candidates, who only took part in the negotiations late in the day, were more likely to be supporters of the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that they had to be met in this extreme way.
Democratic Senator Barrack Obama insisted on the addition of certain dispositions to agree, especially those that would allow owners to keep their homes, and those that affect the salaries of senior employees of state-saved businesses.
'If you ask taxpayers to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of certain persons, that is nothing to be congratulated on.
But these measures are necessary', he explained on the American TV channels.
When asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent John McCain replied: 'I would like to know the details first, but I hope so.
`The guiding principles I have read [show] that this is one thing we will all have to digest, and with which we will be able to move forward.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable,' he said.
The 700 billion dollar plan is aimed at using taxpayers' money
It comes 14 months after a crisis, triggered by the bursting of a real estate bubble, which initially led to the collapse of risk-rich mortgage loans (subprime), before it expanded to further forms of more widespread bonds (PCAA), and finally resulted in a freeze of financial strength and the ruin of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of Republican MPs who failed the first attempt to reach agreement last week.
Since the Democrats have accepted that certain 'poisonous' assets of the societies in distress should only be secured by the government and not purchased, one believes that they will escape the impasse.
In order to round off the perspective for all in Congress, one has also added an order that states that if the government makes losses with this program within five years, it can then levy new taxes in order to get back its invested capital.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first sum of 250 billion, to which a further 100 billion can be added if the President considers it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion must be passed by Congress in a new vote.
In return for his help, Washington will receive shares in the supported companies, which will pay dividends in the event of profits, and will be able to resell it once the storm has passed.
The Federal Government will have the option of halting the attachment procedures for the housing linked to the real estate loans covered by this plan and of setting deadlines for repayment and severance payments to the senior employees of the companies concerned.
The developers of the plan would like the Chamber of Deputies to vote on him today, and then the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
In fact, there were other voices yesterday against this plan, from both the Republicans and the Democrats.
'It's obvious that Washington doesn't understand us,' declared Republican Scott Garett, member of the Chamber's Financial Commission, to his constituents.
'Yes, we have a big financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one that is asking taxpayers to pay for it.'
Democratic MP Brad Sherman, head of a group in Congress called 'The Caucus of Skeptics', presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
'Four hundred excellent economic professors, including three Nobel laureates, have written us to tell us: we ask Congress not to be pressured and to carefully consider which way to go', he said yesterday.
At the same time, we in Europe have again received proof that this is a global crisis.
At an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it would refrain from buying up its competitor, who is in great trouble since she lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US dollars) in the crisis due to the risky real estate loans in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
'This is not a lost money, explained the Dutch Minister of Finance Wouter Bos yesterday.
To compensate, we have the right to vote and influence in the bank.
This is exactly what savers and households appreciate now that uncertain times are coming. '
During this time, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government was in the process of nationalizing another bank, which had been put under pressure by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all ongoing loans from Bank Bradford and Bringley, of which over 41 billion (75.5 billion US dollars) from real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy up the UK bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalized by the British government since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (19252008) - Death of a dedicated icon
His beauty with the azure eyes was his trump card for a long time, no one would say his weakness.
Had the American actor freed himself from the narcissistic mirror with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His sensitivity, his sensitivity and an obvious talent have probably also kept him away from a position of power that gives birth to the really terrible monsters.
But what a great endurance runner!
Paul Newman, who died on Friday at the age of 83 due to lung cancer on his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the golden years.
He was less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and for whom he for a long time was a kind of rival on the screen, more careful in his acting, certainly also more fragile, but just as an apostle of freedom and blasting dramaturgical conventions.
Mixed blood often produces wonderful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 as the son of a German Jew and a Hungarian mother.
From its European roots one of the glorious faces of the American dream should emerge.
Without excessive ego, extreme quality feature.
