This criminal, stormy, violent and unforgettable boxer Rocky Graziano from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role that was intended for James Dean, was re-recorded after his death and made Newman well known in 1956.
This sympathetic ganove in the outstanding The Sting (Der Clou), which was awarded the Oskar for the best film in 1973.
As a bitter and vengeful billiard player in the wonderful The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961),
That face through time, that was him.
Still him.
In his résumé, epochs unite.
The youth know him mainly from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the little Orthodox coach of an ice hockey team.
His fans found him in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers in 1994.
In 2003, Sam Mendes played a final role as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Road to Perdition.
In contrast to several movie legends who retired from the world of film early enough, Newman was to stay in the saddle for a long time, betraying Hollywood, his fortune, his pomp and his concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier saw him, not without humour, as a living challenge to 'underplaying' when he judged his overly expressive achievements.
The metier was not always easy for the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles only flew for a long time.
