What was produced in the invoice factory of Hammer &amp; Co.?
On 8 October, negotiations will begin in the criminal proceedings against Jáno's contract and his accomplices.
In particular, the defendants are accused of participating in organised crime, grossly negligent harm and business fraud, and of other criminal acts, including forgery of documents.
According to the prosecutor's office, the funds derived from the invitations to tender were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often falsified invoices.
State funds and grants from the self-government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have been transferred partly to the funds of the organisation Fiatal Baloldal, partly to the private funds of individual individuals.
As the investigating authorities announced, fictitious invoices were presented when the tender funds were received and the clubs were not supposed to have fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were falsified.
The invoice blocks were bought on the market of Józsefváros, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies to issue invoices was taken on the round trip north of Lake Balaton, to which István Lados of Jáno's supplement was sent.
In the course of this "exploratory tour" Lados was to locate pensions and restaurants.
He asked for bills on consumption in order to later issue invoices based on these templates for the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the self-government of Budapest.
These accounts are said to have been manipulated by István Lados and his accomplice, András ­ri, who, according to our information, was responsible for the constitution of the relevant reports.
One of the destinations of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer restaurant.
As can be seen from two invoices issued by Hammer and Co in 2003, the catering company is said to have hosted the ninety-member group of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
But now the head of the company says that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant at once.
Another invoice, issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also showed serious flaws in form and content.
In a guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at the same time, 130 guests are said to have stayed according to the bill.
The imagination of the bill falsifiers was obviously also limited when it came to the Pigal Kft., a catering company in whose accounting documents of the customers Jobb Jövőért and Hoppa do not appear according to the prosecution.
As Managing Director Győző Farkas informed hvg.hu, it was immediately clear to him that they were falsified documents when documents were submitted to him by the Public Prosecutor's Office during a questioning.
"Our company name and the tax number were wrongly affixed to the stamp".
And further: Apart from formal errors, the fact that the company is said to have accommodated one hundred people after having a total of eleven rooms that are impossible to accommodate so many people was also wrong.
The restaurant was also listed on the invoice as being no longer in service for a long time.
The diligent invoice falsifiers have also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they have targeted offers only travel abroad, and so they have indicated Hungary travel on the cash payment invoice, which also contradicted the company's accounting practice.
As the investigation has shown, they have also referred to VAT on invoices, even though travel agencies' services relating to a country outside the EU are exempt from VAT.
The total amount of VAT was wrong on four invoices issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the company charged only 15 per cent of VAT instead of 25. Moreover, only machine invoices are issued by the employees, but the forged documents were handwritten.
Another mistake that had been made by the "invoicers" was that in one case they had indicated "goods transport" as a service provided, although this is not offered by the company specializing in investment advice, the prosecutor's office informed.
Further formal errors - false invoice format, false stamp - were due to the fact that the invoices issued to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be exposed as counterfeits.
Similarly, in the case of Ravenna Bt. and the Kunfehértó sports camp, whose managing directors claimed never to have issued the invoices.
Another "mistake" was committed by the counterfeiters at the HIB Kft. from Nyíregyháza: this company was in disarray at the time (2001), when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület was supposed to have eaten there - the mass administrator therefore stated not to have issued the invoices himself.
Consciously faked
The other group of invoicers are persons who were well aware that they had to make fictitious invoices.
At the request of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, the Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation issued invoices for the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation, amounting to approximately HUF 4 million.
According to the indictment, the managing director of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoices.
Biogate Kft., which is currently also in liquidation, is also said to have worked with contract and co.: In 2003, the GmbH is said to have supplied the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, as well as the associations Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület with counterfeit invoices with a total value of HUF 5 million, which related to services not provided.
However, there were no payments either, as the invoices were cancelled immediately after their exhibition, but the persons concerned forgot to mention in their documents.
The third group of depositors comprises persons directly associated with the defendants.
One of them is Iván Kubatov, the postman of the Ukrainian managing director of Delta Trió Kft., a Budapest-based, but untraceable fuel and vehicle trading company.
This company is said to have issued several invoices for the sale of computer components with a total value of HUF 18 million between October and December 2005.
According to the investigating authority, the Cash Investment Kft. in liquidation since 14 September 2005 from Kiskunhalas is said to have acted as buyer of these invoices.
The managing director of this company was a Romanian, to whom the company documents were also to be delivered by Iván Kubatov, between 2002 and 2005.
According to our information, Kubatov confessed during the investigation to have issued invoices on behalf of the GmbH. to the associations Atlasz and Hoppa, as well as to Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and to have collected their equivalent.
The companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt. are said to have been founded by Romanian masons on Iván Kubatov's express wish.
