Nevertheless, he was able to benefit from the companies: at the request of his accomplice, the lawyer Zsolt Szente, who was responsible for preparing the company's founding documents, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the clubs associated with the contract, such as Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
In total, Kubatov is said to have issued 15 invoices in the total value of HUF 14.2 million on behalf of the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade.
The prosecutor's office assumes that Kubatov could have collected 10% of the invoice amount and VAT each.
Kubatov is even said to have abused the company Szi-Beri Bt. for issuing fictitious invoices - in this case the invoices were added to the applications of Biztos Pont.
In January 2006, Y-Generáció and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért submitted their applications to the non-profit organization of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány ("TMA").
