Today in Paris, the European Summit on Equal Opportunities began, which is being hosted by the EU Presidency of the Council of the European Union, France.
In her speech to the plenary session, Lívia Járóka, Member of the European People's Party's Fidesz, drew attention in particular to the educational segregation, which is one of the most serious violations of the rights of Roma children, and is also the greatest obstacle to their need for validity.
The high-level conference was opened by French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs Xavier Bertrand, on behalf of the French Presidency, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
