As reported by the Press Office of Fidesz MEPs, Járóka has pointed out that, in addition to discrimination in the search for jobs, Roma are being pushed out of the labour market primarily because of their low educational level.
"The vast majority of Roma youth do not have secondary education, and due to poor primary education, only a small proportion of them can obtain a university degree".
Furthermore, Járóka stressed that education is a fundamental human right, which would play a key role in asserting other human rights.
Investing in the early training of Roma children could strengthen the economy of EU member states.
In the view of the MEPs, it is important that these connections should be as widely understood as possible, i.e. Roma and non-Roma.
Because the earlier a Roma pupil starts school, the more his chances of becoming a productive member of the labour market increase; and by means of income and VAT they make their contribution to national spending.
"As citizens of the Union, the right to quality education for Roma must be guaranteed - poor and segregated education must be stopped" says Lívia Járóka.
As the honourable Member said, a common, goal-oriented and action-oriented approach by the European Union is needed to speed up the process of disegregation in the education sector, with proper compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives being essential.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment and give Roma children the democratic opportunities to contribute to the future of Europe as a fully-fledged citizen," Járóka demanded.
Since last year's congress in Berlin, the summit has been held annually with the aim of creating a unique forum for the promotion of the objectives of equal opportunities and freedom of discrimination at European but also national level, in the sense of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities".
