Brunetta: "From now on breakfast is served before work"
For the first time in the history of Palazzo Chigi there are rotatable doors for the entrances and exits of the officials.
As of today, the measure will come into force against those clever men who first stamp and then drink coffee during working hours.
The new anti-faulples law was presented today by Renato Brunetta, Minister of Public Administration and Mauro Masi, Secretary General of the Council of Ministers' Presidium.
">"Turnable doors are a means of increasing work efficiency through a higher attendance rate and more services", said Minister Brunetta.
"Now begins a new era of responsibility and transparency.
