In particular, the Regional Administrative Court (TAR) is fighting for additional financial compensation for work-related illness, including the planned extension of the mandatory house arrest of the sick worker during which visits can be made and other aspects of the Minister's innovations are challenged.
Napolitano: "Prevention against accidents at work is crucial"
Every day there are 2500 accidents at work in Italy, three people die and 27 remain invalids for life.
For 2007, the Inail (Istituto nazionale contro gli infortuni sul lavoro) data confirm that the fatal accidents at work were around 1200.
These figures show the seriousness of a phenomenon that causes almost twice as many deaths as murders.
Today, the Anmil (Associazione Nazionale Mutilati e Invalidi del Lavoro) will celebrate the 58th national day for the victims of accidents at work in all the provinces of Italy in order to draw the attention of the social institutions and the media to this dramatic situation.
"The worrying data disseminated by Anmil and the tragic news of these days confirm how crucial the issue of prevention in the workplace is," confirms the President of the Republic of Giorgio Napolitano in his communication to the President of the Amil (Associazione nazionale mutilati ed invalidi del lavoro) Pietro Mercandelli.
The head of state expresses his "great appreciation for the constant commitment to prevention in the workplace, to protecting the injured workers, to aid the families of the victims and to raising awareness of public opinion".
"An outraged "basta" has risen to this point; understandable in the case of tragedies, which, measured by their magnitude, cause some vortex in the media and public participation. However, everyday reality often confronts us with dramatic events, which can even be repeated in their own dynamics."
Napolitano does not hide that "there is definitely also a resource problem: it must be invested decisively in education and information."
The numerous initiatives for a more direct awareness in school contexts by young people who feed on the world of work are of particular importance.
It is our duty to focus attention on this phenomenon and not to distract it from its social seriousness. It is necessary to implement and improve a legislative norm.
For his part, the President of the Chamber, Gianfranco Fini, stressed "how the phenomenon of work-related deaths constitutes an urgent social emergency that offends the conscience of all of us and forces all institutions to work towards decisive rules aimed at putting an end to the problem".
"Data on accidents at work seem to indicate a slight improvement, but this does not exclude that the number of work-related deaths is far too high," said Anmil President Pietro Mercandelli.
"We don't want this "positive trend" to mean less attention. That's what causes the tragedy in the end."
"We believe that one does not really do enough to counter the phenomenon of accidents. One can fight against it through various actions.
In our opinion, stronger controls and inspections are necessary – according to Mercandelli, but also stronger measures to educate the workers who already start at school."
"A further effort is needed - he added - in terms of communication and awareness-raising of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon that represents a social emergency is needed."
Mercandelli also referred to "the progressive deterioration of protection for the victims of accidents at work" and denounced the "abolition of the social system against which we have been fighting in recent years".
"The aim is therefore to give the worker a guarantee on insurance so that the fate of the victim of an accident at work does not depend on voluntary or accidental donations decided from time to time by a legislator."
Mp3 player under charge: danger of hearing damage
Listening to loud music over a longer period of time with portable music devices, such as Mp3 players, can lead to permanent hearing damage.
This is reported by the European Commission, which in a report published today in Brussels cites the opinion of the Csrseri (scientific committee on the current and recently identified health risks) of the EU.
"The report states in a note that 5-10 % of those who listen to loud music with portable music equipment for at least five years per week for more than one hour a day risk permanently losing their hearing."
"I am worried that such a large number of young people who usually put portable music devices and mobile phones at a high volume will irretrievably damage their hearing without knowing it," says Meglena Kuneva.
"The scientific findings – according to the Eu – show a clear risk that pushes for rapid action.
What really matters is to sensitize consumers and make this information public.
In the light of these scientific findings, we must re-examine the existing control systems so that they are fully effective and keep up with the new technology".
Brussels had commissioned the independent scientific committee in view of the widespread use of portable music equipment among young people.
"The scientists - the EU Communication concludes - confirm that there is a need for concern and that the European Commission, together with the other EU members and stakeholders, will now examine the necessary measures to better protect children and young people from the noise coming from portable music equipment and similar equipment".
At the moment there is already a European standard which limits the level of noise from portable music equipment to 100 dB, and concerns about the damage that could result from excessive noise pollution.
One can very much limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing the volume and the length of the noise exposure.
In its report, the scientific committee of the Eu points out that if users of portable music equipment only listen to music for five hours a week (more than 89 decibels) so that the legal limits that apply to the maximum noise level at the workplace have already been exceeded.
Those who cross this limit risk a complete loss of hearing within five years.
This would involve 5-10 % of users of such devices, whose number can be estimated at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
Roma, Alemanno launches the "Commission for the Future of the Capital"
We'll start today, it's supposed to be over in March, we'll take stock in June.
This is the procedure laid down by the Capitol for the work of the Commission for the Future of the Capital of Rome, which met this morning in the new headquarters behind the Caracalla thermal baths.
In six months, President Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will work out the leadership lines for Rome.
Once the project is completed, the City Council and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects in order to be able to present the strategic plan for Rome in June with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and the Mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The Commission is absolutely independent and all political, social and cultural opinions are represented in it", Alemanno stresses. "It will present proposals for a development plan for Rome, whose political leaders will remain the city council and the municipal council.
There is no redistribution of responsibilities, only the will to have a place where one can develop a great project for Rome.
In March their task will be completed and the Commission will dissolve, as such a project must have a timed end point.
In June - as the Lord Mayor announced - we will present the strategic plan in which we will use the work done by the Commission".
Anyone who questions the Commission's competence, since it lacks a sense of responsibility, replies to Alemanno: "Everything depends on the work that the Commission will do and the quality of its proposals.
If, like the Attali Commission in France, it delivers quality results – and this will certainly be the case in Rome – then its contribution will be fundamental.
Too often politics deals with the everyday problems and emergencies that occur from time to time.
We, on the other hand, want to have a longer period of time in mind, so that we can work seriously on the development of Rome and the future of the city in a deeper perspective".
The Mayor of Rome attaches great importance to clarifying the following: "This Commission is neither a useless institution nor a wreck: it is absolutely free, it will not cost the Roman citizens a penny and it will make us think. It will employ the best minds of the capital".
According to Alemanno, "it is necessary to have a strategic plan that is neither hermetically nor static in order to enable our city to make a leap in quality - which it really needs - and thus to take a joint step into the future".
A future, according to the Mayor of Rome, which "will not only be limited to the current municipal boundaries, but will look much further", not only as regards the role of Rome as the metropolis and political capital of Italy, but also as the future capital of Europe and the Mediterranean."
