The elite are in danger
The phenomenon had already been revealed a few days ago when the Chamber of Deputies voted against the $700 billion White House package: a large part of the Americans were and is more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday's issue of the New York Times, which reports on how the crisis is gradually dividing the Republican party, which is increasingly dividing itself into its old and moderate East Coast soul, which has always favored state institutions and business community, and those neo-conservatives that are hostile to "those in Washington" and the financial world, and wins voters, especially in the south and the center of the states.
This part of the party owes its rise above all to the voice of the one I mentioned above.
However, this example just mentioned is only a small part of the major changes that the current economic earthquake heralds or even already represents: not only in the US, but also throughout the West and perhaps beyond it will be affected by it.
In both states and in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the long-afraid events that are finally taking shape and coming to light under these new conditions.
The first of these phenomena is the new discovery, the unprecedented renaissance of the state in connection with a kind of renationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis means the decline of banking and financial institutions, which have close links with foreign countries and at the same time manage an enormous amount of the assets of private households that live in a single state.
This is an immediate political problem for governments: how to behave towards the families concerned, which are also an enormous mass of voters.
The crisis therefore appears global economically, but politically it is almost purely national.
Political internationalism seems to have been sidelined by itself and lost its right to speak: the clear proof of this has been given by the EU, which, due to its division into various national and international conflicts, cannot find a common path.
Therefore, everyone now expects the intervention of their own state; rescue plans, new rules, and above all distribution of aid funds: Since the crisis became more and more serious, only the US in the economic situation can save itself without external help.
And in addition to the means, they also have the legitimacy to use them: thus two conditions that cannot be overvalued – under certain circumstances – to which no other international organisation and no market will be able to resort in a similar way.
The new emphasis placed on the state-national element is, moreover, perfectly in line with the ever-increasing importance which has recently been associated in the economy with a closely related sector: territoriality.
Paradoxically, it is right now, when we were so convinced that we have long since entered a networked empire, a realm of ever differentiated technologies, of the intangible, that we must suddenly see how our future will depend more and more on the essential material things: water, harvest and oil.
These can certainly all be transported from one place to the other of the world, but are nevertheless inextricably linked to a narrowly defined piece of earth – a territory.
Therefore, the one who has such a territory is advantageous to another who lives in an unharvested, waterless or oil-free area.
I now come to the second novelty, which, however, requires a short insertion.
Who territory, who government, who says politics, also says leadership.
In this sense, the financial crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, there is the knowledge of the need for respected leaderships, that is, the need for someone who knows how to regulate things.
On the other hand, there is now a wave of indignation at the existing leaderships, especially those of the economy, which have turned out to be insufficient and full of shadow zones.
Finally, there is a deeper and, in a certain sense, even more disturbing aspect: a loss of confidence, an intolerance, a picture of impracticality, a feeling of distance, all directed towards a whole class of managers of Western countries.
It seems to be the conviction among large parts of the population that it is not only the actions of the social elite, but already their world of ideas, their way of life, their culture in the broadest sense of the word, whose content is presented to the majority as increasingly foreign and traditional.
The demand for leadership thus feeds underground a branched but powerful movement of the disempowerment of the leading class and the conventional political establishment. This manifests itself in unforeseen "revolts" of the voters and in the sudden change of the collective state of mind of recent times: beginning with the rise of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, through the collapse of the Labour Party in Britain, to the rebellion of the American MPs against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the right in Italy also plays a role here).
One gets the impression that the old elite, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, magazines, intellectuals, creditors, some would say their format, more and more problems of understanding and therefore less representative value in terms of what is going on in the lower social strata of the West today and is being intensified by the financial crisis and driven to over-dimensionality.
In view of all this, it would simply be exaggerated to speak of a "rebellion of the masses".
But keeping your eyes wide open is certainly not.
The super glue that blows up walls
To defeat the forces of gravity thanks to an adhesive and to be able to climb up walls like Superman.
This is the subject of four American research centres, one of which now seems to have almost reached its destination.
With a glue applied on a surface of only 2.5 qcm, the researchers succeeded in fixing a body weighing 100 kg on a vertical wall.
The STUDIO – an American journal that has published the results of researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material invented by the research team is a further development of the adhesives already used, which use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged into a stack of spaghetti," explains Zhong Lin Wang from the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists have been inspired by the feet of the geckos, which are covered by microscopic hairs that give the animal a perfect hold.
The tests carried out with various materials such as glass Teflon and sandpaper have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the holding capacity of the reptiles' feet and at the same time "can be removed from the wall without any problems," says Liming Dai, a researcher at the Faculty of Engineering at Dayton University.
"This material could be used as a transitory adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Like Spiderman walking up on walls? Maybe so, but the researchers think of a less fascinating benefit, such as the connection of electrical devices, because the nanotubes are also conductors of heat and electricity.
Other fields of application could be in the field of space.
So for now, the superheroes have to wait.
THE OTHER TYPE OF RESEARCH – including the University of Berkeley, California, is dedicated to a new type of adhesive.
In an article by the American Chemical Society, the Californian scientists present a microfiber adhesive that cleans itself from dust like hair by moving on a surface and thus always retains a perfect adhesion.
Medicines: never take with fruit juice
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed because of their refreshing quality and vitamin richness, especially in the summer, can cause serious health damage if they are taken with certain vital medicines, as they can have an extreme effect on the absorption of these by the body.
David Bailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, repeatedly pointed out the risk of both packaged and fresh fruit juices in connection with drug intake. At the 236th meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he once again sounded the alarm: A glass of apple, orange or grapefruit juice is sufficient to reduce the absorption capacity of certain vital drugs to the extent that they are practically eliminated and thus endangers the health of patients.
Grapefruit juice was already suspected of being responsible for increasing the effects of some drugs, such as antibiotics, antiasthmatics, cardiovascular drugs, anxiolytic and neurological agents, to toxic levels.
MEDICAMENTS IN DRIVER – The same agency of the medicine had warned doctors and patients of the dangers of this mix in a report two years ago, stressing that attention should be paid to what is drunk in combination with drugs such as diazepane or metadone.
IT IS NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT – According to the experts, orange juice and apple juice also contain substances that can inhibit the medicines.
The list of active substances inhibited by fruit juices is long.
Hence the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Università Statale di Milano: "These results are usually immediately forwarded to the various international manufacturers who are so free to change consumer information.
It is therefore recommended to always read the package leaflet and, if there are still uncertainties, to ask a pharmacist or doctor not to be shy," emphasizes the expert of the Ansa Agency.
