Open Office, the third version of the "Anti-Microsoft" package appears
The OpenOffice.org 3.0 release day has come; the open source software gains an increasing number of users, both at home and in the office, both among freelancers and in the public administration, as a free replacement for Microsoft's Office.
After a year of intensive work by the voluntary developers, which is monitored by SUN Microsystems, the new Open Office is now presenting itself to the public with some new features: in addition to a revised and now spartan initial menu, a completely guaranteed compatibility with Apple's Mac OS x operating system has finally been achieved, as well as support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2 format, i.e. the latest standard ISO version.
In 2007, Microsoft's Office released a new version of OpenOffice (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Also interesting are some new features, such as the one that allows to reduce the size of PowerPoint presentations, which makes sending via email easier. This also includes the possibility to import PDF files into graphics editing modules and at the same time to preserve the original appearance of the page.
Thus, "hybrid" PDF files can now be generated, which extend the typical graphic of the Adobe format by the elements of a table and a word processing system.
The collaboration is one of the most improved elements of the applications: tables can now be edited by several hands by different users, thus avoiding conflicts in the event of changes; in the case of the word processing system, a Frabe is assigned to each processor, in order to guarantee a better correction procedure.
Some companies are currently publishing various features of OpenOffice on the Internet (on the cloud), while the final result is to be published in the coming weeks.
The Italian version is available for download on the following link: http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html. Thus it follows the English version, which has been on the mirrors since Friday.
Except for Windows and Mac OS, the program is also available for the Linux operating system.
On request, you can send the installation CD to your home or office.
However, if the cost-freeness can be an incentive for the dissemination of the programme in private households, it is also particularly in the area of business, where OpenOffice could succeed the big throw: after all, various institutions of the public administration and schools have already moved to OpenOffice.
In fact, there is not even a lack of training, which means optimal help for small and medium-sized enterprises, and thus even opens up business prospects.
OpenOffice consists of five main components: Writer, the Word-related text creation program; Calc, the spreadsheet program aimed at pushing Excel; Impress, for creating presentations such as PowerPoint; Dbase for operating databases instead of more popular access; and most recently Draw, a graphics module.
The goal for 2008 is to achieve 5 million downloads – a goal that can be easily exceeded with already reached 3 million and 600 thousand.
