The housing market for students knows no crises.
According to the recent investigation of Sunia, the tenant union, a single room can cost a student up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
"This phenomenon has already taken on very serious aspects.A large number of students are thus effectively losing their right to study, as their families are unable to support them at this level" – according to Sunia's leader, Laura Mariani – "in these cities, the high demand from the students leads to a deforming of the market, which has also damaged the other inhabitants.
In addition, most rental offers include a number of violations: free contracts, missing registrations, without rental price limit, unauthorized sub-rents.
For the Sunia, there is a need for exceptional measures, which lead to lower rental prices through a revision of taxation.
Looking more closely at the study, it turns out that in Milan a sleeping space in the Brianza district is needed for about 450 euros; a single room starts at 650 euros (in the Bande Nere district) and ends at 800 euros in the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera district or even 900 euros in the Vittoria district.
In Florence a sleeping space costs an average of 350/400 euros, a room 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in the neighborhoods around the university, 250/280 euros are needed for a place to sleep, 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome the prices in the neighborhoods around the university are about 600 euros for a single room, 450 for a sleeping place in a double room.
Only a little lower are the rents in the neighbourhoods around the other universities of Rome: 550 euros in Ostiense and Cinecittà.
Only those who avoid in outskirts can save money: 300 euros for a sleeping place and 450 euros for a single room in Prenestina, Centocelle and similar quarters.
In Naples you need 300-450 euros for a place to sleep, for one room the price is between 400 and 600 euros in the most expensive neighborhoods, the Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari a sleeping place costs 250-350 euros, a single room at least 350.
In the smallest cities, prices are lower, but they are more important in the urban economy.
In the cities where the phenomenon of renting to non-European students is more frequent, such as in Perugia, there is even another anomaly: a rent that is 25-30% higher than the average is required by foreign students.
Goodbye to the old cinema Paradiso – the cities close their historic cinemas
The historical cinemas close due to the favored multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is happening in the major urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which began with the birth of the large multi-room complexes in the periphery, in the long run means death for the one-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the features of a cultural crime.
The film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", which brought him the Oscar and the Grand Prix of Cannes 20 years ago, is about the history of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a cinema world that is probably lost forever. "It is like losing a friend, with whom you have covered a piece of street full of emotions", says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso".
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak a clear language: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these mines paid for most of the cinemas in the major cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This shows that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy leads the lists, 81 in Tuscany as well as in Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "although it is useful that new structures also emerge, the first priority is the preservation of the already existing one, because including a hall in the city, not all of its regular customers are willing to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association external eight: the debt burden recorded by the state amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a disgrace from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not comply with the existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros per year would be needed".
It is interesting to note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, because of the fears surrounding the old cinemas, decided to protect them by means of an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first such agreement in Italy, which aims to protect and support traditional cinemas, both in the historical centre and in the periphery.
Among the measures envisaged are tax advantages for cinema operators as well as benefits for the public in terms of local transport: it will be allowed to travel to the traffic-limited areas of the centre and also to park at cheaper parking fees.
"It is a gratifying initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will follow our example and also design new concepts.
Of course, we also need better audio and video equipment in order to be able to do something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema has always been an important topic for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to start the "Nuovo cinema Paradiso", even though I had been playing with the idea for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or Quirinale in Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn aside so as not to have to see the dust-covered posters.
The links between politics and 'Ndrangheta lead to the arrest of the mayor of Gioia Tauro
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adapt the decisions of the municipality to the interests of the mafia group Piromalli.
The accusations made by the Anti-Mafia authorities of Calabria against the mayor Giorgio Dal Torrione and his deputy Rosario Schiavone of Gioia Tauro, who were arrested this morning for involvement in mafia activities, are serious.
In handcuffs, Gioacchino Piromalli, the older mediator between the clan and the public administration, and his nephew, the lawyer, who bears the same name as the clan's boss, had already been convicted of involvement in criminal associations of the mafia, at that time to a sum of 10 million euros.
"Despite any kind of moral and legal norm," the lawyers write, "the two local administrations decided to pay the lawyer Piromalli funds for consulting activities."
"This made it possible for the mafia group – according to the judges – to enter the town halls officially and to co-determine the policy of the public administration."
The President of the Calabrian Regional Committee Agazio Loiero does not deny that in his region "it is anything but an exception to encounter links between local administrations and organised crime." "There are places where the concentration of the mafia is greater than in others where such links are practically inevitable.
But there are also local politicians who resist the pressure of the 'Ndrangheta: heroes who maintain a white vest."
This morning's arrests follow those of last July, which according to the police of the Clan Piromalli were beheaded.
Since the end of last April, the municipal council of Gioia Tauro had been dissolved, but already in 1991 – and even then due to alleged links between organized crime and local administration – local politicians had been removed from their municipal offices.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, then mayor of the Udc, was elected head of the centre-right coalition after the May 2006 runoff.
He screamed scandal when the prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He referred to the Deputy Minister of the Interior, Marco Minniti, whom he accused of having invented everything for political-strategic reasons, but the judges, in connection with this morning's arrest warrant, state that the Piromalli clan had even dared to apply for a change to the A3 project.
From an interception campaign in connection with the investigations into the Dal Torrione case, the willingness to respond to the wishes of an entrepreneur, who is known to be a representative of the large group around the Piromalli – which has made public administration measures identical to the interests of this clan."
When the energy comes out of the waves, suddenly the big ones run up
It is a non-drinking source of money covering over 70% of the planet's surface, and only now do the great energy companies in the world seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and are also looking to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has been considered and investigated for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now environmental organizations and the rise in oil prices are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of global energy needs could be covered by ocean waves.
This would be equivalent to twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides would also be added.
Giants in the attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, more and more companies from the traditional energy industry are now relying on marine energy production.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies," said the spokesperson of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal, and is considering the opportunity to work with us."
This is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is not to be underestimated, especially considering that oil continues to be mined by the US, particularly in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; even if the details are not known, observers are talking about increasing interest.
Technologies still need to be improved.
Experts are talking about a technology that is still in the process, not least because the last doubts on the part of environmentalists have not yet been resolved.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland have a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are various possibilities: Ocean Power uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The thrust of the waves, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
It drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The current is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for state approval. Part of the energy gained could also be used for military facilities.
Verdant Power, however, is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using submarine turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator through the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long line of potential clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Research, the potential that is present in the tides now deserves special interest.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
Tidal energy in particular is what led states like New York, Maine and Alaska as well as other coastal states to invest already 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – for 2009 up to 35 million are already planned.
